

📘 Day 20 – Challenge: Detecting Duplicates



🏆 Main Challenge: Check for Duplicates

let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 1];

// Use a Set to check uniqueness
let hasDuplicate = new Set(numbers).size !== numbers.length;

if (hasDuplicate) {
  console.log("Duplicates found");
} else {
  console.log("No duplicates");
}
// Output: "Duplicates found"

👉 Kid-style explanation:
Think of giving every student in class a roll number 🎒.

If two kids get the same roll number ➝ 🚨 duplicate!

If everyone has a unique roll number ➝ ✅ no duplicates.



---

📝 Assignment 1: Check for Duplicate Orders

let orders = [101, 102, 103, 104, 101];

let hasDuplicateOrders = new Set(orders).size !== orders.length;

console.log(hasDuplicateOrders ? "Duplicates found" : "No duplicates");
// Output: "Duplicates found"

👉 Order IDs should always be unique—if two customers get the same ID, chaos! 🧾


---

📝 Assignment 2: Duplicate Items in Shopping Cart

let cart = ["Rice", "Dal", "Oil", "Rice"];

let hasDuplicateItems = new Set(cart).size !== cart.length;

console.log(hasDuplicateItems ? "Duplicates found" : "No duplicates");
// Output: "Duplicates found"

👉 Imagine a cart where you accidentally add Rice twice—that’s a duplicate 🛒.


---

📝 Assignment 3: Duplicate Numbers in Weekly Sales

let weekly_sales = [5000, 6000, 7000, 5000, 8000];

let hasDuplicateSales = new Set(weekly_sales).size !== weekly_sales.length;

console.log(hasDuplicateSales ? "Duplicates found" : "No duplicates");
// Output: "Duplicates found"

👉 If sales on Monday and Thursday are both ₹5000, then it’s a duplicate 📊.


---

✨ Summary (Day 11):

Duplicates = repeated values in a list.

Easy trick → Convert to Set and compare size with original list.

Useful in orders 🧾, shopping carts 🛒, weekly sales 📈, or student IDs 🎓.



---

⚡ Pro Tip: You can also count duplicates:

let arr = [1, 2, 2, 3, 4, 4, 4];
let count = {};

arr.forEach(num => count[num] = (count[num] || 0) + 1);

console.log(count); // { '1': 1, '2': 2, '3': 1, '4': 3 }

👉 This not only detects duplicates but also tells you how many times they occur!



